    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "A journalist is editing an article and wants to compare the names of two companies to decide which one should be listed first in a report.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Article</code> class, complete the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareCompanies()</code> method. This method should:\r\n\r\n- Use <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareTo()</code> to compare two company names (stored in instance variables)\r\n- Return the result of that comparison as an integer\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">ArticleRunner</code> class, create an <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Article</code> object using two company names, then call <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareCompanies()</code> and print the result.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareTo()</code> returns:\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>A negative number if the first company comes before the second</li>\r\n  <li>Zero if the names are equal</li>\r\n  <li>A positive number if the first company comes after the second</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n",
